# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lte-networks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lte-networks/4g] The earliest deployed technologies marketed as "4G" were Long-Term Evolution (LTE), developed by the 3GPP group, and Mobile Worldwide Interoperability for Microwave Access (Mobile WiMAX), based on IEEE specifications.
[src:lte-networks/4g] These provided significant enhancements over previous 3G and 2G.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Since the first-release versions of Mobile WiMAX and LTE support much less than 1 Gbit/s peak bit rate, they are not fully IMT-Advanced compliant, but are often branded 4G by service providers.
[src:lte-networks/4g] According to operators, a generation of the network refers to the deployment of a new non-backward-compatible technology.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Both the original LTE and WiMAX standards had previously sometimes been referred to as 3.9G/3.95G.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The ITU's new definition for 4G also included Evolved High Speed Packet Access (HSPA+).
[src:lte-networks/4g] Mobile WiMAX Release 2 (also known as *WirelessMAN-Advanced* or *IEEE 802.16m*) and LTE Advanced (LTE-A) are IMT-Advanced compliant backwards compatible versions of the above two systems, standardized during the spring 2011, and promising speeds in the order of 1 Gbit/s.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In January 2012, the ITU backtracked on its previous definition for 4G, claiming that Mobile WiMAX 2 and LTE Advanced are "true 4G" while their predecessors are "transitional" 3G-4G.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As opposed to earlier generations, a 4G system does not support traditional circuit-switched telephony service, but instead relies on all-Internet Protocol (IP) based communication such as IP telephony.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The peak bit rate is further improved by smart antenna arrays for multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) communications.
[src:lte-networks/4g] New mobile generations have appeared about every ten years since the first move from 1981 analog (1G) to digital (2G) transmission in 1992.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This was followed, in 2001, by 3G multi-media support, spread spectrum transmission and a minimum peak bit rate of 200 kbit/s, in 2011/2012 to be followed by "real" 4G, which refers to all-IP packet-switched networks giving mobile ultra-broadband (gigabit speed) access.
[src:lte-networks/4g] While the ITU has adopted recommendations for technologies that would be used for future global communications, they do not actually perform the standardization or development work themselves, instead relying on the work of other standard bodies such as IEEE, WiMAX Forum, and 3GPP.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In the mid-1990s, the ITU-R standardization organization released the IMT-2000 requirements as a framework for what standards should be considered 3G systems, requiring 2000 kbit/s peak bit rate.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In theory speeds up to 672 Mbit/s are possible, but have not been deployed yet.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The fastest 3G-based standard in the CDMA2000 family is the EV-DO Rev.
[src:lte-networks/4g] B, which is available since 2010 and offers 15.67 Mbit/s downstream.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In 2008, ITU-R specified the IMT Advanced (International Mobile Telecommunications Advanced) requirements for 4G systems.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This article refers to 4G using IMT-Advanced (*International Mobile Telecommunications Advanced*), as defined by ITU-R.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In September 2009, the technology proposals were submitted to the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) as 4G candidates.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Implementations of Mobile WiMAX and first-release LTE were largely considered a stopgap solution that would offer a considerable boost until WiMAX 2 (based on the 802.16m specification) and LTE Advanced was deployed.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The latter's standard versions were ratified in spring 2011.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The first set of 3GPP requirements on LTE Advanced was approved in June 2008.
[src:lte-networks/4g] LTE Advanced was standardized in 2010 as part of Release 10 of the 3GPP specification.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Some sources consider first-release LTE and Mobile WiMAX implementations as pre-4G or near-4G, as they do not fully comply with the planned requirements of 1 Gbit/s for stationary reception and 100 Mbit/s for mobile.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Confusion has been caused by some mobile carriers who have launched products advertised as 4G but which according to some sources are pre-4G versions, commonly referred to as 3.9G, which do not follow the ITU-R defined principles for 4G standards, but today can be called 4G according to ITU-R.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Vodafone Netherlands for example, advertised LTE as 4G, while advertising LTE Advanced as their '4G+' service.
[src:lte-networks/4g] LTE Advanced (Long-Term Evolution Advanced) is a candidate for IMT-Advanced standard, formally submitted by the 3GPP organization to ITU-T in the fall 2009, and as of 2013 has been released to the public.The target of 3GPP LTE Advanced is to reach and surpass the ITU requirements.
[src:lte-networks/4g] LTE Advanced is essentially an enhancement to LTE.
[src:lte-networks/4g] It is not a new technology, but rather an improvement on the existing LTE network.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This upgrade path makes it more cost effective for vendors to offer LTE and then upgrade to LTE Advanced which is similar to the upgrade from WCDMA to HSPA.
[src:lte-networks/4g] LTE and LTE Advanced will also make use of additional spectrums and multiplexing to allow it to achieve higher data speeds.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Coordinated Multi-point Transmission will also allow more system capacity to help handle the enhanced data speeds.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The IEEE 802.16m or WirelessMAN-Advanced (WiMAX 2) evolution of 802.16e is under development, with the objective to fulfill the IMT-Advanced criteria of 1 Gbit/s for stationary reception and 100 Mbit/s for mobile reception.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The pre-4G 3GPP Long-Term Evolution (LTE) technology is often branded "4G – LTE", but the first LTE release does not fully comply with the IMT-Advanced requirements.
[src:lte-networks/4g] LTE has a theoretical net bit rate capacity of up to 100 Mbit/s in the downlink and 50 Mbit/s in the uplink if a 20 MHz channel is used – and more if multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO), i.e. antenna arrays, are used.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The physical radio interface was at an early stage named *High Speed OFDM Packet Access* (HSOPA), now named Evolved UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access (E-UTRA).
[src:lte-networks/4g] The first LTE USB dongles do not support any other radio interface.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The world's first publicly available LTE service was opened in the two Scandinavian capitals, Stockholm (Ericsson and Nokia Siemens Networks systems) and Oslo (a Huawei system) on December 14, 2009, and branded 4G.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The user terminals were manufactured by Samsung.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As of November 2012, the five publicly available LTE services in the United States are provided by MetroPCS, Verizon Wireless, AT&T Mobility, U.S.
[src:lte-networks/4g] T-Mobile Hungary launched a public beta test (called *friendly user test*) on 7 October 2011, and has offered commercial 4G LTE services since 1 January 2012.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In South Korea, SK Telecom and LG U+ have enabled access to LTE service since 1 July 2011 for data devices, slated to go nationwide by 2012.
[src:lte-networks/4g] KT Telecom closed its 2G service by March 2012 and completed nationwide LTE service in the same frequency around 1.8 GHz by June 2012.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In the United Kingdom, LTE services were launched by EE in October 2012, by O2 and Vodafone in August 2013, and by Three in December 2013.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The Mobile WiMAX (IEEE 802.16e-2005) mobile wireless broadband access (MWBA) standard (also known as WiBro in South Korea) is sometimes branded 4G, and offers peak data rates of 128 Mbit/s downlink and 56 Mbit/s uplink over 20 MHz wide channels.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In June 2006, the world's first commercial mobile WiMAX service was opened by KT in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Sprint has begun using Mobile WiMAX, as of 29 September 2008, branding it as a "4G" network even though the current version does not fulfill the IMT Advanced requirements on 4G systems.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In Russia, Belarus and Nicaragua WiMax broadband internet access were offered by a Russian company Scartel, and was also branded 4G, Yota.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In the latest version of the standard, WiMax 2.1, the standard has been updated to be not compatible with earlier WiMax standard, and is instead interchangeable with LTE-TDD system, effectively merging WiMax standard with LTE.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As Long-Term Evolution (LTE) and WiMAX were adopted by the global telecommunications industry, LTE emerged as a primary 4G standard and saw significant adoption in the Chinese market.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Although TD-LTE, one of the two LTE air interface variants, was initially less mature than its FDD-LTE counterpart, various domestic and international wireless carriers eventually adopted the technology..
[src:lte-networks/4g] IBM's data shows that 67% of the operators are considering LTE because this is the main source of their future market.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The above news also confirms IBM's statement that while only 8% of the operators are considering the use of WiMAX, WiMAX can provide the fastest network transmission to its customers on the market and could challenge LTE.
[src:lte-networks/4g] TD-LTE is not the first 4G wireless mobile broadband network data standard, but it is China's 4G standard that was amended and published by China's largest telecom operator – China Mobile.
[src:lte-networks/4g] After a series of field trials, is expected to be released into the commercial phase in the next two years.
[src:lte-networks/4g] UMB (Ultra Mobile Broadband) was the brand name for a discontinued 4G project within the 3GPP2 standardization group to improve the CDMA2000 mobile phone standard for next generation applications and requirements.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In November 2008, Qualcomm, UMB's lead sponsor, announced it was ending development of the technology, favoring LTE instead.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The objective was to achieve data speeds over 275 Mbit/s downstream and over 75 Mbit/s upstream.
[src:lte-networks/4g] At an early stage the Flash-OFDM system was expected to be further developed into a 4G standard.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The iBurst system (or HC-SDMA, High Capacity Spatial Division Multiple Access) was at an early stage considered to be a 4G predecessor.
[src:lte-networks/4g] It was later further developed into the Mobile Broadband Wireless Access (MBWA) system, also known as IEEE 802.20.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As opposed to earlier generations, 4G systems do not support circuit switched telephony.
[src:lte-networks/4g] IEEE 802.20, UMB and OFDM standards lack soft-handover support, also known as cooperative relaying.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Recently, new access schemes like Orthogonal FDMA (OFDMA), Single Carrier FDMA (SC-FDMA), Interleaved FDMA, and Multi-carrier CDMA (MC-CDMA) are gaining more importance for the next generation systems.
[src:lte-networks/4g] These are based on efficient FFT algorithms and frequency domain equalization, resulting in a lower number of multiplications per second.
[src:lte-networks/4g] They also make it possible to control the bandwidth and form the spectrum in a flexible way.
[src:lte-networks/4g] However, they require advanced dynamic channel allocation and adaptive traffic scheduling.
[src:lte-networks/4g] WiMax is using OFDMA in the downlink and in the uplink.
[src:lte-networks/4g] For the LTE (telecommunication), OFDMA is used for the downlink; by contrast, Single-carrier FDMA is used for the uplink since OFDMA contributes more to the PAPR related issues and results in nonlinear operation of amplifiers.
[src:lte-networks/4g] IFDMA provides less power fluctuation and thus requires energy-inefficient linear amplifiers.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Similarly, MC-CDMA is in the proposal for the IEEE 802.20 standard.
[src:lte-networks/4g] These access schemes offer the same efficiencies as older technologies like CDMA.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Apart from this, scalability and higher data rates can be achieved.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The other important advantage of the above-mentioned access techniques is that they require less complexity for equalization at the receiver.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This is an added advantage especially in the MIMO environments since the spatial multiplexing transmission of MIMO systems inherently require high complexity equalization at the receiver.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In addition to improvements in these multiplexing systems, improved modulation techniques are being used.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Whereas earlier standards largely used Phase-shift keying, more efficient systems such as 64QAM are being proposed for use with the 3GPP Long-Term Evolution standards.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Unlike 3G, which is based on two parallel infrastructures consisting of circuit switched and packet switched network nodes, 4G is based on packet switching *only*.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This requires low-latency data transmission.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As IPv4 addresses are (nearly) exhausted, IPv6 is essential to support the large number of wireless-enabled devices that communicate using IP.
[src:lte-networks/4g] By increasing the number of IP addresses available, IPv6 removes the need for network address translation (NAT), a method of sharing a limited number of addresses among a larger group of devices, which has a number of problems and limitations.
[src:lte-networks/4g] When using IPv6, some kind of NAT is still required for communication with legacy IPv4 devices that are not also IPv6-connected.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As of June 2009, Verizon has posted specifications that require any 4G devices on its network to support IPv6.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The performance of radio communications depends on an antenna system, termed smart or intelligent antenna.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Recently, multiple antenna technologies are emerging to achieve the goal of 4G systems such as high rate, high reliability, and long range communications.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In the early 1990s, to cater for the growing data rate needs of data communication, many transmission schemes were proposed.
[src:lte-networks/4g] One technology, spatial multiplexing, gained importance for its bandwidth conservation and power efficiency.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Spatial multiplexing involves deploying multiple antennas at the transmitter and at the receiver.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Independent streams can then be transmitted simultaneously from all the antennas.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This technology, called MIMO (as a branch of intelligent antenna), multiplies the base data rate by (the smaller of) the number of transmit antennas or the number of receive antennas.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Apart from this, the reliability in transmitting high speed data in the fading channel can be improved by using more antennas at the transmitter or at the receiver.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This is called *transmit* or *receive diversity*.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Both transmit/receive diversity and transmit spatial multiplexing are categorized into the space-time coding techniques, which does not necessarily require the channel knowledge at the transmitter.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The other category is closed-loop multiple antenna technologies, which require channel knowledge at the transmitter.
[src:lte-networks/4g] One of the key technologies for 4G and beyond is called Open Wireless Architecture (OWA), supporting multiple wireless air interfaces in an open architecture platform.
[src:lte-networks/4g] SDR is one form of open wireless architecture (OWA).
[src:lte-networks/4g] Since 4G is a collection of wireless standards, the final form of a 4G device will constitute various standards.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This can be efficiently realized using SDR technology, which is categorized to the area of the radio convergence.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In 1991, WiLAN founders Hatim Zaghloul and Michel Fattouche invented wideband orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (WOFDM), the basis for wideband wireless communication applications, including 4G mobile communications.
[src:lte-networks/4g] The 4G system was originally envisioned by the DARPA, the US Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Since the 2.5G GPRS system, cellular systems have provided dual infrastructures: packet switched nodes for data services, and circuit switched nodes for voice calls.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In 4G systems, the circuit-switched infrastructure is abandoned and only a packet-switched network is provided, while 2.5G and 3G systems require both packet-switched and circuit-switched network nodes, i.e. two infrastructures in parallel.
[src:lte-networks/4g] This means that in 4G traditional voice calls are replaced by IP telephony.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Since 2009, the LTE-Standard has strongly evolved over the years, resulting in many deployments by various operators across the globe.
[src:lte-networks/4g] For an overview of commercial LTE networks and their respective historic development see: List of LTE networks.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Among the vast range of deployments, many operators are considering the deployment and operation of LTE networks.
[src:lte-networks/4g] A compilation of planned LTE deployments can be found at: List of planned LTE networks.
[src:lte-networks/4g] 4G introduces a potential inconvenience for those who travel internationally or wish to switch carriers.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In order to make and receive 4G voice calls (VoLTE), the subscriber handset must not only have a matching frequency band (and in some cases require unlocking), it must also have the matching enablement settings for the local carrier and/or country.
[src:lte-networks/4g] A major issue in 4G systems is to make the high bit rates available in a larger portion of the cell, especially to users in an exposed position in between several base stations.
[src:lte-networks/4g] In current research, this issue is addressed by macro-diversity techniques, also known as group cooperative relay, and also by Beam-Division Multiple Access (BDMA).
[src:lte-networks/4g] Pervasive networks are an amorphous and at present entirely hypothetical concept where the user can be simultaneously connected to several wireless access technologies and can seamlessly move between them (See vertical handoff, IEEE 802.21).
[src:lte-networks/4g] These access technologies can be Wi-Fi, UMTS, EDGE, or any other future access technology.
[src:lte-networks/4g] Included in this concept is also smart-radio (also known as cognitive radio) technology to efficiently manage spectrum use and transmission power as well as the use of mesh routing protocols to create a pervasive network.
[src:lte-networks/4g] As of 2023, many countries and regions have started the transition from 4G to 5G, the next generation of cellular technology.
[src:lte-networks/4g] 5G promises even faster speeds, lower latency, and the ability to connect a vast number of devices simultaneously.
[src:lte-networks/4g] 4G networks are expected to coexist with 5G networks for several years, providing coverage in areas where 5G is not available.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The SAE has a flat, all-IP architecture with separation of control plane and user plane traffic.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The main component of the SAE architecture is the **Evolved Packet Core** (**EPC**), also known as **SAE Core**.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The EPC will serve as the equivalent of GPRS networks (via the **Mobility Management Entity**, **Serving Gateway** and **PDN Gateway** subcomponents).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The MME is the key control-node for the LTE access-network.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It is responsible for idle mode User Equipment (UE) paging and tagging procedure including retransmissions.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It is involved in the bearer activation/deactivation process and is also responsible for choosing the Serving Gateway for a UE at the initial attach and at time of intra-LTE handover involving Core Network (CN) node relocation.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It is responsible for authenticating the user (by interacting with the Home Subscriber Server).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The Non Access Stratum (NAS) signaling terminates at the MME and it is also responsible for generation and allocation of temporary identities to UEs.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It checks the authorization of the UE to camp on the service provider's Public Land Mobile Network (PLMN) and enforces UE roaming restrictions.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The MME is the termination point in the network for ciphering/integrity protection for NAS signaling and handles the security key management.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Lawful interception of signaling is also supported by the MME.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The MME also provides the control plane function for mobility between LTE and 2G/3G access networks with the S3 interface terminating at the MME from the SGSN.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The MME also terminates the S6a interface towards the HSS for roaming UEs.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] For idle state User Equipment, the Serving Gateway terminates the downlink data path and triggers paging when downlink data arrives for the User Equipment.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It manages and stores UE contexts, e.g. parameters of the IP bearer service, network internal routing information.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It also performs replication of the user traffic in case of lawful interception.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The Packet Data Network Gateway (PDN Gateway, also PGW) provides connectivity from the User Equipment (UE) to external packet data networks (PDNs) by being its point of exit and entry of traffic.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] A piece of User Equipment may have simultaneous connectivity with more than one Packet Data Network Gateway for accessing multiple packet data networks.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The PDN Gateway performs policy enforcement, packet filtering for each user, charging support, lawful interception and packet screening.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Another key role of the Packet Data Network Gateway is to act as the anchor for mobility between 3GPP and non-3GPP technologies such as WiMAX and 3GPP2 (CDMA 1X and EvDO).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The Home Subscriber Server is a central database that contains user-related and subscription-related information.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The functions of the HSS include mobility management, call and session establishment support, user authentication and access authorization.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The HSS is based on pre-Rel-4 Home Location Register (HLR) and Authentication Center (AuC).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The ANDSF provides information to the UE about connectivity to 3GPP and non-3GPP access networks (such as Wi-Fi).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The purpose of the ANDSF is to assist the UE to discover the access networks in their vicinity and to provide rules (policies) to prioritize and manage connections to these networks.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The main function of the ePDG is to secure the data transmission with a UE connected to the EPC over untrusted non-3GPP access, e.g.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] For this purpose, the ePDG acts as a termination node of IPsec tunnels established with the UE.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The Non-Access Stratum (NAS) protocols form the highest stratum of the control plane between the user equipment (UE) and MME.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] NAS protocols support the mobility of the UE and the session management procedures to establish and maintain IP connectivity between the UE and a PDN GW.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] They define the rules for a mapping between parameters during inter-system mobility with 3G networks or non-3GPP access networks.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] They also provide the NAS security by integrity protection and ciphering of NAS signaling messages.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] EPS (Evolved Packet System) provides the subscriber with a "ready-to-use" IP connectivity and an "always-on" experience by linking between mobility management and session management procedures during the UE attach procedure.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Complete NAS transactions consist of specific sequences of elementary procedures with EPS Mobility Management (EMM) and EPS Session Management (ESM) protocols.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The EPS (Evolved Packet System) Mobility Management (EMM) protocol provides procedures for the control of mobility when the User Equipment (UE) uses the Evolved UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access Network (E-UTRAN).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It also provides control of security for the NAS protocols.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The UE and the network execute the attach procedure, the default EPS bearer context activation procedure in parallel.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] During the EPS attach procedure the network activates a default EPS bearer context.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The EPS session management messages for the default EPS bearer context activation are transmitted in an information element in the EPS mobility management messages.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The UE and network complete the combined default EPS bearer context activation procedure and the attach procedure before the dedicated EPS bearer context activation procedure is completed.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The success of the attach procedure is dependent on the success of the default EPS bearer context activation procedure.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] If the attach procedure fails, then the ESM session management procedures also fails.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The EPS Session Management (ESM) protocol provides procedures for the handling of EPS bearer contexts.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Together with the bearer control provided by the Access Stratum, it provides the control of user plane bearers.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The transmission of ESM messages is suspended during EMM procedures except for the attach procedure.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Generally, ESM procedures can be performed only if an EMM context has been established between the UE and the MME, and the secure exchange of NAS messages has been initiated by the MME by use of the EMM procedures.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Once the UE is successfully attached, the UE can request the MME to set up connections to additional PDNs.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] For each additional connection, the MME activates a separate default EPS bearer context.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] A default EPS bearer context remains activated throughout the lifetime of the connection to the PDN.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The MME maintains EMM context and EPS bearer context information for UEs in the ECM-IDLE, ECM CONNECTED and EMM-DEREGISTERED states.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] MME supports the S1 interface with eNodeB.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The integrated S1 MME interface stack consists of IP, SCTP, S1AP.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] MME supports S11 interface with Serving Gateway.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The integrated S11 interface stack consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-C.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Sxa: since 3GPP Rel.14, the Sx interface and the associated PFCP protocol was added to the SGW, allowing for the Control User Plane Separation between SGW-C and SGW-U.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] SGW supports S11 interface with MME and S5/S8 interface with PGW.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The integrated control plane stack for these interfaces consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-C.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] SGW supports the S1-U interface with eNodeB and S5/S8 data plane interface with PGW.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The integrated data plane stack for these interfaces consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-U.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Gz: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Offline Charging System (OFCS), mainly to send the Charging Data Records (CDRs) of the post-paid users via FTP.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Gy: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Online Charging System (OCS).
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The P-GW informs the charging system about pre-paid users payload in real time.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Diameter protocol is used in the Gy interface.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Gx: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Policy and Charging Rules Function (PCRF) in order to handle Policy and Charging Rules (PCC) rules.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] These rules contain charging related information as well as quality of service (QoS) parameters that will be used in the bearer establishment.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Diameter protocol is used in the Gx interface.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] SGi: this interface is defined between the P-GW and external networks, for example, Internet access, corporate access, etc.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] Sxb: since 3GPP Rel.14, the Sx interface and the associated PFCP protocol was added to the PGW, allowing for the Control User Plane Separation between PGW-C and PGW-U.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It does not have a circuit-switched domain, which is traditionally used for phone calls and SMS.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] CSFB and SMS over SGs are seen as interim solutions, the long term being IMS.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The UE can connect to the EPC using several access technologies.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It is up to the network operator to decide whether a non-3GPP access technology is trusted or untrusted.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] It is worth noting that these trusted/untrusted categories do not apply to 3GPP accesses.
[src:lte-networks/evolved-packet-core] The 3GPP delivers standards in parallel releases, which compose consistent sets of specifications and features.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In cellular telecommunications, **handover**, or **handoff**, is the process of transferring an ongoing call or data session from one channel connected to the core network to another channel.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In satellite communications it is the process of transferring satellite control responsibility from one earth station to another without loss or interruption of service.
[src:lte-networks/handover] American English uses the term *handoff*, and this is most commonly used within some American organizations such as 3GPP2 and in American originated technologies such as CDMA2000.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In British English the term *handover* is more common, and is used within international and European organisations such as ITU-T, IETF, ETSI and 3GPP, and standardised within European originated standards such as GSM and UMTS.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The term handover is more common in academic research publications and literature, while handoff is slightly more common within the IEEE and ANSI organisations.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The most basic form of handover is when a phone call in progress is redirected from its current cell (called *source*) to a new cell (called *target*).
[src:lte-networks/handover] In terrestrial networks the source and the target cells may be served from two different cell sites or from one and the same cell site (in the latter case the two cells are usually referred to as two *sectors* on that cell site).
[src:lte-networks/handover] Such a handover, in which the source and the target are different cells (even if they are on the same cell site) is called *inter-cell* handover.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The purpose of inter-cell handover is to maintain the call as the subscriber is moving out of the area covered by the source cell and entering the area of the target cell.
[src:lte-networks/handover] A special case is possible, in which the source and the target are one and the same cell and only the used channel is changed during the handover.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Such a handover, in which the cell is not changed, is called *intra-cell* handover.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The purpose of intra-cell handover is to change one channel, which may be interfered or fading with a new clearer or less fading channel.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Is one in which the channel in the source cell is released and only then the channel in the target cell is engaged.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Hard handovers are intended to be instantaneous in order to minimize the disruption to the call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] A hard handover is perceived by network engineers as an event during the call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] It requires the least processing by the network providing service.
[src:lte-networks/handover] When the mobile is between base stations, then the mobile can switch with any of the base stations, so the base stations bounce the link with the mobile back and forth.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Is one in which the channel in the source cell is retained and used for a while in parallel with the channel in the target cell.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The interval, during which the two connections are used in parallel, may be brief or substantial.
[src:lte-networks/handover] For this reason the soft handover is perceived by network engineers as a state of the call, rather than a brief event.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Soft handovers may involve using connections to more than two cells: connections to three, four or more cells can be maintained by one phone at the same time.
[src:lte-networks/handover] When a call is in a state of soft handover, the signal of the best of all used channels can be used for the call at a given moment or all the signals can be combined to produce a clearer copy of the signal.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Softer handovers are possible when the cells involved in the handovers have a single cell site.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Handover can also be classified on the basis of handover techniques used.
[src:lte-networks/handover] An advantage of the hard handover is that at any moment in time one call uses only one channel.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The hard handover event is indeed very short and usually is not perceptible by the user.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In the old analog systems it could be heard as a click or a very short beep; in digital systems it is unnoticeable.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Another advantage of the hard handover is that the phone's hardware does not need to be capable of receiving two or more channels in parallel, which makes it cheaper and simpler.
[src:lte-networks/handover] A disadvantage is that if a handover fails the call may be temporarily disrupted or even terminated abnormally.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Technologies which use hard handovers, usually have procedures which can re-establish the connection to the source cell if the connection to the target cell cannot be made.
[src:lte-networks/handover] However re-establishing this connection may not always be possible (in which case the call will be terminated) and even when possible the procedure may cause a temporary interruption to the call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] One advantage of the soft handovers is that the connection to the source cell is broken only when a reliable connection to the target cell has been established and therefore the chances that the call will be terminated abnormally due to failed handovers are lower.
[src:lte-networks/handover] However, by far a bigger advantage comes from the mere fact that simultaneously channels in multiple cells are maintained and the call could only fail if all of the channels are interfered or fade at the same time.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Fading and interference in different channels are unrelated and therefore the probability of them taking place at the same moment in all channels is very low.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Thus the reliability of the connection becomes higher when the call is in a soft handover.
[src:lte-networks/handover] This advantage comes at the cost of more complex hardware in the phone, which must be capable of processing several channels in parallel.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Another price to pay for soft handovers is use of several channels in the network to support just a single call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] This reduces the number of remaining free channels and thus reduces the capacity of the network.
[src:lte-networks/handover] By adjusting the duration of soft handovers and the size of the areas in which they occur, the network engineers can balance the benefit of extra call reliability against the price of reduced capacity.
[src:lte-networks/handover] While theoretically speaking soft handovers are possible in any technology, analog or digital, the cost of implementing them for analog technologies is prohibitively high and none of the technologies that were commercially successful in the past (e.g.
[src:lte-networks/handover] AMPS, TACS, NMT, etc.) had this feature.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Of the digital technologies, those based on FDMA also face a higher cost for the phones (due to the need to have multiple parallel radio-frequency modules) and those based on TDMA or a combination of TDMA/FDMA, in principle, allow not so expensive implementation of soft handovers.
[src:lte-networks/handover] However, none of the 2G (second-generation) technologies have this feature (e.g.
[src:lte-networks/handover] On the other hand, all CDMA based technologies, 2G and 3G (third-generation), have soft handovers.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In all current commercial technologies based on FDMA or on a combination of TDMA/FDMA (e.g.
[src:lte-networks/handover] GSM, AMPS, IS-136/DAMPS, etc.) changing the channel during a hard handover is realised by changing the pair of used transmit/receive frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/handover] For the practical realisation of handovers in a cellular network each cell is assigned a list of potential target cells, which can be used for handing over calls from this source cell to them.
[src:lte-networks/handover] These potential target cells are called *neighbors* and the list is called *neighbor list*.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Creating such a list for a given cell is not trivial and specialized computer tools are used.
[src:lte-networks/handover] They implement different algorithms and may use for input data from field measurements or computer predictions of radio wave propagation in the areas covered by the cells.
[src:lte-networks/handover] During a call one or more parameters of the signal in the channel in the source cell are monitored and assessed in order to decide when a handover may be necessary.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The downlink (forward link) and/or uplink (reverse link) directions may be monitored.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The handover may be requested by the phone or by the base station (BTS) of its source cell and, in some systems, by a BTS of a neighboring cell.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The phone and the BTSes of the neighboring cells monitor each other's signals and the best target candidates are selected among the neighboring cells.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In some systems, mainly based on CDMA, a target candidate may be selected among the cells which are not in the neighbor list.
[src:lte-networks/handover] This is done in an effort to reduce the probability of interference due to the aforementioned near–far effect.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In CDMA systems, 2G and 3G, the most common criterion for requesting a handover is Ec/Io ratio measured in the pilot channel (CPICH) and/or RSCP.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In CDMA systems, when the phone in soft or softer handover is connected to several cells simultaneously, it processes the received in parallel signals using a rake receiver.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Each signal is processed by a module called *rake finger*.
[src:lte-networks/handover] A usual design of a rake receiver in mobile phones includes three or more rake fingers used in soft handover state for processing signals from as many cells and one additional finger used to search for signals from other cells.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The set of cells, whose signals are used during a soft handover, is referred to as the *active set*.
[src:lte-networks/handover] If the search finger finds a sufficiently-strong signal (in terms of high Ec/Io or RSCP) from a new cell this cell is added to the active set.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The cells in the neighbour list (called in CDMA *neighbouring set*) are checked more frequently than the rest and thus a handover with a neighbouring cell is more likely, however a handover with others cells outside the neighbor list is also allowed (unlike in GSM, IS-136/DAMPS, AMPS, NMT, etc.).
[src:lte-networks/handover] There are occurrences where a handoff is unsuccessful.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Much research has been dedicated to this problem.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The source of the problem was discovered in the late 1980s.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Because frequencies cannot be reused in adjacent cells, when a user moves from one cell to another, a new frequency must be allocated for the call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] If a user moves into a cell when all available channels are in use, the user's call must be terminated.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Also, there is the problem of signal interference where adjacent cells overpower each other resulting in receiver desensitization.
[src:lte-networks/handover] There are also inter-technology handovers where a call's connection is transferred from one access technology to another, e.g. a call being transferred from GSM to UMTS or from CDMA IS-95 to CDMA2000.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The 3GPP UMA/GAN standard enables GSM/UMTS handoff to Wi-Fi and vice versa.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Different systems have different methods for handling and managing handoff request.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Some systems handle handoff in same way as they handle new originating call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In such system the probability that the handoff will not be served is equal to blocking probability of new originating call.
[src:lte-networks/handover] But if the call is terminated abruptly in the middle of conversation then it is more annoying than the new originating call being blocked.
[src:lte-networks/handover] So in order to avoid this abrupt termination of ongoing call handoff request should be given priority to new call this is called as handoff prioritization.
[src:lte-networks/handover] In this technique, a fraction of the total available channels in a cell is reserved exclusively for handoff request from ongoing calls which may be handed off into the cell.
[src:lte-networks/handover] Queuing of handoffs is possible because there is a finite time interval between the time the received signal level drops below handoff threshold and the time the call is terminated due to insufficient signal level.
[src:lte-networks/handover] The delay size is determined from the traffic pattern of a particular service area.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In telecommunications, **Long Term Evolution** (**LTE**) is a standard for wireless broadband communication for cellular mobile devices and data terminals.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] It is considered to be a "transitional" 4G technology, and is therefore also referred to as **3.95G** as a step above 3G.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE is based on the 2G GSM/EDGE and 3G UMTS/HSPA standards.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] It improves on those standards' capacity and speed by using a different radio interface and core network improvements.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE is the upgrade path for carriers with both GSM/UMTS networks and CDMA2000 networks.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE has been succeeded by LTE Advanced, which is officially defined as a "true" 4G technology and also named "LTE+".
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The standard is developed by the 3GPP (3rd Generation Partnership Project) and is specified in its Release 8 document series, with minor enhancements described in Release 9.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE is also called **3.95G** and has been marketed as **4G LTE** and **Advanced 4G**; but the original version did not meet the technical criteria of a 4G wireless service, as specified in the 3GPP Release 8 and 9 document series for LTE Advanced.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE Advanced standard formally satisfies the ITU-R requirements for being considered IMT-Advanced.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] To differentiate LTE Advanced and WiMAX-Advanced from the then current 4G technologies, ITU has defined in January 2012 the latter as "True 4G".
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE stands for Long Term Evolution and is a registered trademark owned by ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) for the wireless data communications technology and development of the GSM/UMTS standards.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] However, other nations and companies do play an active role in the LTE project.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The goal of LTE was to increase the capacity and speed of wireless data networks using new DSP (digital signal processing) techniques and modulations that were developed around the turn of the millennium.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] A further goal was the redesign and simplification of the network architecture to an IP-based system with significantly reduced transfer latency compared with the 3G architecture.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE wireless interface is incompatible with 2G and 3G networks, so it must be operated on a separate radio spectrum.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The idea of LTE was first proposed in 1998, with the use of the COFDM radio access technique to replace the CDMA and studying its Terrestrial use in the L band at 1428 MHz (TE) In 2004 by Japan's NTT Docomo, with studies on the standard officially commenced in 2005.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In May 2007, the LTE/SAE Trial Initiative (LSTI) alliance was founded as a global collaboration between vendors and operators with the goal of verifying and promoting the new standard to ensure the global introduction of the technology as quickly as possible.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard was finalized in December 2008, and the first publicly available LTE service was launched by TeliaSonera in Oslo and Stockholm on December 14, 2009, as a data connection with a USB modem.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In Canada, Rogers Wireless was the first to launch LTE network on July 7, 2011, offering the Sierra Wireless AirCard 313U USB mobile broadband modem, known as the "LTE Rocket stick" then followed closely by mobile devices from both HTC and Samsung.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The next version of LTE is LTE Advanced, which was standardized in March 2011.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Additional evolution known as LTE Advanced Pro was approved in 2015.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE specification provides downlink peak rates of 300 Mbit/s, uplink peak rates of 75 Mbit/s, and QoS provisions permitting a transfer latency of less than 5 ms in the radio access network.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE has the ability to manage fast-moving mobiles and supports multicast and broadcast streams.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE supports scalable carrier bandwidths, from 1.4 MHz to 20 MHz and supports both frequency division duplexing (FDD) and time-division duplexing (TDD).
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The IP-based network architecture, called the Evolved Packet Core (EPC) designed to replace the GPRS Core Network, supports seamless handovers for both voice and data to cell towers with older network technology such as GSM, UMTS and CDMA2000.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The simpler architecture results in lower operating costs (for example, each E-UTRA cell will support up to four times the data and voice capacity supported by HSPA).
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Because LTE frequencies and bands differ from country to country, only multi-band phones can use LTE in all countries where it is supported.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Most carriers supporting GSM or HSUPA networks can be expected to upgrade their networks to LTE at some stage.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The following is a list of the top 10 countries/territories by 4G LTE coverage as measured by OpenSignal.com in February/March 2019.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] For the complete list of all the countries/territories, see list of countries by 4G LTE penetration.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] There are two major differences between LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD: how data is uploaded and downloaded, and what frequency spectra the networks are deployed in.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] While LTE-FDD uses paired frequencies to upload and download data, LTE-TDD uses a single frequency, alternating between uploading and downloading data through time.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The ratio between uploads and downloads on a LTE-TDD network can be changed dynamically, depending on whether more data needs to be sent or received.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD also operate on different frequency bands, with LTE-TDD working better at higher frequencies, and LTE-FDD working better at lower frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Frequencies used for LTE-TDD range from 1850 MHz to 3800 MHz, with several different bands being used.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE-TDD spectrum is generally cheaper to access, and has less traffic.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Further, the bands for LTE-TDD overlap with those used for WiMAX, which can easily be upgraded to support LTE-TDD.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Despite the differences in how the two types of LTE handle data transmission, LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD share 90 percent of their core technology, making it possible for the same chipsets and networks to use both versions of LTE.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] A number of companies produce dual-mode chips or mobile devices, including Samsung and Qualcomm, while operators CMHK and Hi3G Access have developed dual-mode networks in Hong Kong and Sweden, respectively.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The creation of LTE-TDD involved a coalition of international companies that worked to develop and test the technology.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] China Mobile was an early proponent of LTE-TDD, along with other companies like Datang Telecom and Huawei, which worked to deploy LTE-TDD networks, and later developed technology allowing LTE-TDD equipment to operate in white spaces—frequency spectra between broadcast TV stations.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Intel also participated in the development, setting up a LTE-TDD interoperability lab with Huawei in China, as well as ST-Ericsson, Nokia, and Nokia Siemens (now Nokia Solutions and Networks), which developed LTE-TDD base stations that increased capacity by 80 percent and coverage by 40 percent.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Qualcomm also participated, developing the world's first multi-mode chip, combining both LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD, along with HSPA and EV-DO.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Accelleran, a Belgian company, has also worked to build small cells for LTE-TDD networks.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Trials of LTE-TDD technology began as early as 2010, with Reliance Industries and Ericsson India conducting field tests of LTE-TDD in India, achieving 80 megabit-per second download speeds and 20 megabit-per-second upload speeds.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] By 2011, China Mobile began trials of the technology in six cities.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Although initially seen as a technology utilized by only a few countries, including China and India, by 2011 international interest in LTE-TDD had expanded, especially in Asia, in part due to LTE-TDD's lower cost of deployment compared to LTE-FDD.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] By the middle of that year, 26 networks around the world were conducting trials of the technology.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The Global LTve (GTI) was also started in 2011, with founding partners China Mobile, Bharti Airtel, SoftBank Mobile, Vodafone, Clearwire, Aero2 and E-Plus.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In September 2011, Huawei announced it would partner with Polish mobile provider Aero2 to develop a combined LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD network in Poland, and by April 2012, ZTE Corporation had worked to deploy trial or commercial LTE-TDD networks for 33 operators in 19 countries.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In late 2012, Qualcomm worked extensively to deploy a commercial LTE-TDD network in India, and partnered with Bharti Airtel and Huawei to develop the first multi-mode LTE-TDD smartphone for India.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In Japan, SoftBank Mobile launched LTE-TDD services in February 2012 under the name **Advanced eXtended Global Platform** (AXGP), and marketed as SoftBank 4G (ja).
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The AXGP band was previously used for Willcom's PHS service, and after PHS was discontinued in 2010 the PHS band was re-purposed for AXGP service.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In the U.S., Clearwire planned to implement LTE-TDD, with chipmaker Qualcomm agreeing to support Clearwire's frequencies on its multi-mode LTE chipsets.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] With Sprint's acquisition of Clearwire in 2013, the carrier began using these frequencies for LTE service on networks built by Samsung, Alcatel-Lucent, and Nokia.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] As of March 2013, 156 commercial 4G LTE networks existed, including 142 LTE-FDD networks and 14 LTE-TDD networks.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] As of November 2013, the South Korean government planned to allow a fourth wireless carrier in 2014, which would provide LTE-TDD services, and in December 2013, LTE-TDD licenses were granted to China's three mobile operators, allowing commercial deployment of 4G LTE services.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In January 2014, Nokia Solutions and Networks indicated that it had completed a series of tests of voice over LTE (VoLTE) calls on China Mobile's TD-LTE network.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The next month, Nokia Solutions and Networks and Sprint announced that they had demonstrated throughput speeds of 2.6 gigabits per second using a LTE-TDD network, surpassing the previous record of 1.6 gigabits per second.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Much of the LTE standard addresses the upgrading of 3G UMTS to what will eventually be 4G mobile communications technology.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] A large amount of the work is aimed at simplifying the architecture of the system, as it transitions from the existing UMTS circuit + packet switching combined network to an all-IP flat architecture system.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard supports only packet switching with its all-IP network.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Voice calls in GSM, UMTS, and CDMA2000 are circuit switched, so with the adoption of LTE, carriers will have to re-engineer their voice call network.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, LTE just provides data services, and when a voice call is to be initiated or received, it will fall back to the circuit-switched domain.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] , and therefore, can provide services quickly.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] However, the disadvantage is a longer call setup delay.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, the handset works simultaneously in the LTE and circuit-switched modes, with the LTE mode providing data services and the circuit-switched mode providing the voice service.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The disadvantage of this solution is that the phone can become expensive with high power consumption.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] One additional approach that is not initiated by operators is the usage of over-the-top content (OTT) services, using applications like Skype and Google Talk to provide LTE voice service.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Most major backers of LTE preferred and promoted VoLTE from the beginning.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The lack of software support in initial LTE devices, as well as core network devices, however, led to a number of carriers promoting VoLGA (Voice over LTE Generic Access) as an interim solution.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] The idea was to use the same principles as GAN (Generic Access Network, also known as UMA or Unlicensed Mobile Access), which defines the protocols through which a mobile handset can perform voice calls over a customer's private Internet connection, usually over wireless LAN.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] VoLGA however never gained much support, because VoLTE (IMS) promises much more flexible services, albeit at the cost of having to upgrade the entire voice call infrastructure.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] VoLTE may require Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) to be able to smoothly perform a handover to a 2G or 3G network in case of poor LTE signal quality.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] While the industry has standardized on VoLTE, early LTE deployments required carriers to introduce circuit-switched fallback as a stopgap measure.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] When placing or receiving a voice call on a non-VoLTE-enabled network or device, LTE handsets will fall back to old 2G or 3G networks for the duration of the call.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] To ensure compatibility, 3GPP demands at least AMR-NB codec (narrow band), but the recommended speech codec for VoLTE is Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband, also known as HD Voice.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] This codec is mandated in 3GPP networks that support 16 kHz sampling.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Fraunhofer IIS has proposed and demonstrated "Full-HD Voice", an implementation of the AAC-ELD (Advanced Audio Coding – Enhanced Low Delay) codec for LTE handsets.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Where previous cell phone voice codecs only supported frequencies up to 3.5 kHz and upcoming wideband audio services branded as *HD Voice* up to 7 kHz, Full-HD Voice supports the entire bandwidth range from 20 Hz to 20 kHz.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] For end-to-end Full-HD Voice calls to succeed, however, both the caller's and recipient's handsets, as well as networks, have to support the feature.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] As a result, phones from one country may not work in other countries.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] Users will need a multi-band capable phone for roaming internationally.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] According to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute's (ETSI) intellectual property rights (IPR) database, about 50 companies have declared, as of March 2012, holding essential patents covering the LTE standard.
[src:lte-networks/lte-telecommunication] This is less than the combined published rates, due to reduced-rate licensing agreements, such as cross-licensing.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In telecommunications, **orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing** (**OFDM**) is a type of digital transmission used in digital modulation for encoding digital (binary) data on multiple carrier frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM has developed into a popular scheme for wideband digital communication, used in applications such as digital television and audio broadcasting, DSL internet access, wireless networks, power line networks, and 4G/5G mobile communications.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is a frequency-division multiplexing (FDM) scheme that was introduced by Robert W.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In OFDM, the incoming bitstream representing the data to be sent is divided into multiple streams.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Multiple closely spaced orthogonal subcarrier signals with overlapping spectra are transmitted, with each carrier modulated with bits from the incoming stream so multiple bits are being transmitted in parallel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Demodulation is based on fast Fourier transform algorithms.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM was improved by Weinstein and Ebert in 1971 with the introduction of a guard interval, providing better orthogonality in transmission channels affected by multipath propagation.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Each subcarrier (signal) is modulated with a conventional modulation scheme (such as quadrature amplitude modulation or phase-shift keying) at a low symbol rate.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This maintains total data rates similar to conventional single-carrier modulation schemes in the same bandwidth.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Channel equalization is simplified because OFDM may be viewed as using many slowly modulated narrowband signals rather than one rapidly modulated wideband signal.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In **coded orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing** (**COFDM**), forward error correction (convolutional coding) and time/frequency interleaving are applied to the signal being transmitted.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This is done to overcome errors in mobile communication channels affected by multipath propagation and Doppler effects.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] COFDM was introduced by Alard in 1986 for Digital Audio Broadcasting for Eureka Project 147.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In practice, OFDM has become used in combination with such coding and interleaving, so that the terms COFDM and OFDM co-apply to common applications.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The following list is a summary of existing OFDM-based standards and products.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] For further details, see the Usage section at the end of the article.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The advantages and disadvantages listed below are further discussed in the Characteristics and principles of operation section below.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In OFDM, the subcarrier frequencies are chosen so that the subcarriers are orthogonal to each other, meaning that crosstalk between the sub-channels is eliminated and inter-carrier guard bands are not required.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This greatly simplifies the design of both the transmitter and the receiver; unlike conventional FDM, a separate filter for each sub-channel is not required.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The orthogonality requires that the **subcarrier spacing** is $\scriptstyle \Delta f\,=\,{\frac {k}{T_{U}}}$ Hertz, where *T*U seconds is the useful symbol duration (the receiver-side window size), and *k* is a positive integer, typically equal to 1.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This stipulates that each carrier frequency undergoes *k* more complete cycles per symbol period than the previous carrier.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Therefore, with *N* subcarriers, the total passband bandwidth will be *B* ≈ *N*·Δ*f* (Hz).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The orthogonality also allows high spectral efficiency, with a total symbol rate near the Nyquist rate for the equivalent baseband signal (i.e., near half the Nyquist rate for the double-side band physical passband signal).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Almost the whole available frequency band can be used.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM generally has a nearly 'white' spectrum, giving it benign electromagnetic interference properties with respect to other co-channel users.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] (or an integer multiple of that) for orthogonality.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If a guard interval is applied (see below), Nyquist bandwidth requirement would be even lower.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If no guard interval was applied, this would result in a base band complex valued signal with a sample rate of 1 MHz, which would require a baseband bandwidth of 0.5 MHz according to Nyquist.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, the passband RF signal is produced by multiplying the baseband signal with a carrier waveform (i.e., double-sideband quadrature amplitude-modulation) resulting in a passband bandwidth of 1 MHz.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A single-side band (SSB) or vestigial sideband (VSB) modulation scheme would achieve almost half that bandwidth for the same symbol rate (i.e., twice as high spectral efficiency for the same symbol alphabet length).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] It is however more sensitive to multipath interference.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM requires very accurate frequency synchronization between the receiver and the transmitter; with frequency deviation the subcarriers will no longer be orthogonal, causing *inter-carrier interference* (ICI) (i.e., cross-talk between the subcarriers).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Frequency offsets are typically caused by mismatched transmitter and receiver oscillators, or by Doppler shift due to movement.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] While Doppler shift alone may be compensated for by the receiver, the situation is worsened when combined with multipath, as reflections will appear at various frequency offsets, which is much harder to correct.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This effect typically worsens as speed increases, and is an important factor limiting the use of OFDM in high-speed vehicles.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In order to mitigate ICI in such scenarios, one can shape each subcarrier in order to minimize the interference resulting in a non-orthogonal subcarriers overlapping.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Other ICI suppression techniques usually drastically increase the receiver complexity.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The orthogonality allows for efficient modulator and demodulator implementation using the FFT algorithm on the receiver side, and inverse FFT on the sender side.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Although the principles and some of the benefits have been known since the 1960s, OFDM is popular for wideband communications today by way of low-cost digital signal processing components that can efficiently calculate the FFT.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The time to compute the inverse-FFT or FFT has to take less than the time for each symbol, which for example for DVB-T (FFT 8k) means the computation has to be done in 896 µs or less.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The computational demand approximately scales linearly with FFT size so a double size FFT needs double the amount of time and vice versa.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] As a comparison an Intel Pentium III CPU at 1.266 GHz is able to calculate a 8192 point FFT in 576 µs using FFTW.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Intel Pentium M at 1.6 GHz does it in 387 µs.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Intel Core Duo at 3.0 GHz does it in 96.8 µs.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Since the duration of each symbol is long, it is feasible to insert a guard interval between the OFDM symbols, thus eliminating the intersymbol interference.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The guard interval also eliminates the need for a pulse-shaping filter, and it reduces the sensitivity to time synchronization problems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A simple example: If one sends a million symbols per second using conventional single-carrier modulation over a wireless channel, then the duration of each symbol would be one microsecond or less.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This imposes severe constraints on synchronization and necessitates the removal of multipath interference.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If the same million symbols per second are spread among one thousand sub-channels, the duration of each symbol can be longer by a factor of a thousand (i.e., one millisecond) for orthogonality with approximately the same bandwidth.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Assume that a guard interval of 1/8 of the symbol length is inserted between each symbol.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Intersymbol interference can be avoided if the multipath time-spreading (the time between the reception of the first and the last echo) is shorter than the guard interval (i.e., 125 microseconds).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This corresponds to a maximum difference of 37.5 kilometers between the lengths of the paths.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The cyclic prefix, which is transmitted during the guard interval, consists of the end of the OFDM symbol copied into the guard interval, and the guard interval is transmitted followed by the OFDM symbol.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The reason that the guard interval consists of a copy of the end of the OFDM symbol is so that the receiver will integrate over an integer number of sinusoid cycles for each of the multipaths when it performs OFDM demodulation with the FFT.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In some standards such as Ultrawideband, in the interest of transmitted power, cyclic prefix is skipped and nothing is sent during the guard interval.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The receiver will then have to mimic the cyclic prefix functionality by copying the end part of the OFDM symbol and adding it to the beginning portion.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The effects of frequency-selective channel conditions, for example fading caused by multipath propagation, can be considered as constant (flat) over an OFDM sub-channel if the sub-channel is sufficiently narrow-banded (i.e., if the number of sub-channels is sufficiently large).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This makes frequency domain equalization possible at the receiver, which is far simpler than the time-domain equalization used in conventional single-carrier modulation.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In OFDM, the equalizer only has to multiply each detected subcarrier (each Fourier coefficient) in each OFDM symbol by a constant complex number, or a rarely changed value.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] On a fundamental level, simpler digital equalizers are better because they require fewer operations, which translates to fewer round-off errors in the equalizer.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Those round-off errors can be viewed as numerical noise and are inevitable.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] complex multiplications per OFDM symbol; i.e., one million multiplications per second, at the receiver).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] [this is imprecise: over half of these complex multiplications are trivial, i.e. = to 1 and are not implemented in software or HW]. complex-valued multiplications per OFDM symbol (i.e., 10 million multiplications per second), at both the receiver and transmitter side.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] would require, in a naive implementation, 125 multiplications per symbol (i.e., 125 million multiplications per second).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If differential modulation such as DPSK or DQPSK is applied to each subcarrier, equalization can be completely omitted, since these non-coherent schemes are insensitive to slowly changing amplitude and phase distortion.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Some of the subcarriers in some of the OFDM symbols may carry pilot signals for measurement of the channel conditions (i.e., the equalizer gain and phase shift for each subcarrier).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Pilot signals and training symbols (preambles) may also be used for time synchronization (to avoid intersymbol interference, ISI) and frequency synchronization (to avoid inter-carrier interference, ICI, caused by Doppler shift).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM was initially used for wired and stationary wireless communications.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, with an increasing number of applications operating in highly mobile environments, the effect of dispersive fading caused by a combination of multi-path propagation and doppler shift is more significant.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Over the last decade, research has been done on how to equalize OFDM transmission over doubly selective channels.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is invariably used in conjunction with channel coding (forward error correction), and almost always uses frequency and/or time interleaving.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Frequency (subcarrier) interleaving increases resistance to frequency-selective channel conditions such as fading.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] For example, when a part of the channel bandwidth fades, frequency interleaving ensures that the bit errors that would result from those subcarriers in the faded part of the bandwidth are spread out in the bit-stream rather than being concentrated.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Similarly, time interleaving ensures that bits that are originally close together in the bit-stream are transmitted far apart in time, thus mitigating against severe fading as would happen when travelling at high speed.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, time interleaving is of little benefit in slowly fading channels, such as for stationary reception, and frequency interleaving offers little to no benefit for narrowband channels that suffer from flat-fading (where the whole channel bandwidth fades at the same time).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A similar design of audio data encoding makes compact disc (CD) playback robust.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A classical type of error correction coding used with OFDM-based systems is convolutional coding, often concatenated with Reed-Solomon coding.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Usually, additional interleaving (on top of the time and frequency interleaving mentioned above) in between the two layers of coding is implemented.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Newer systems, however, usually now adopt near-optimal types of error correction codes that use the turbo decoding principle, where the decoder iterates towards the desired solution.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Examples of such error correction coding types include turbo codes and LDPC codes, which perform close to the Shannon limit for the Additive White Gaussian Noise (AWGN) channel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Some systems that have implemented these codes have concatenated them with either Reed-Solomon (for example on the MediaFLO system) or BCH codes (on the DVB-S2 system) to improve upon an error floor inherent to these codes at high signal-to-noise ratios.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The resilience to severe channel conditions can be further enhanced if information about the channel is sent over a return-channel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Based on this feedback information, adaptive modulation, channel coding and power allocation may be applied across all subcarriers, or individually to each subcarrier.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In the latter case, if a particular range of frequencies suffers from interference or attenuation, the carriers within that range can be disabled or made to run slower by applying more robust modulation or error coding to those subcarriers.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The term **discrete multitone modulation** (**DMT**) denotes OFDM-based communication systems that adapt the transmission to the channel conditions individually for each subcarrier, by means of so-called *bit-loading*.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The upstream and downstream speeds can be varied by allocating either more or fewer carriers for each purpose.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Some forms of rate-adaptive DSL use this feature in real time, so that the bitrate is adapted to the co-channel interference and bandwidth is allocated to whichever subscriber needs it most.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM in its primary form is considered as a digital modulation technique, and not a multi-user channel access method, since it is used for transferring one bit stream over one communication channel using one sequence of OFDM symbols.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, OFDM can be combined with multiple access using time, frequency or coding separation of the users.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In orthogonal frequency-division multiple access (OFDMA), frequency-division multiple access is achieved by assigning different OFDM sub-channels to different users.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDMA supports differentiated quality of service by assigning different number of subcarriers to different users in a similar fashion as in CDMA, and thus complex packet scheduling or medium access control schemes can be avoided.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDMA is also a candidate access method for the IEEE 802.22 *Wireless Regional Area Networks* (WRAN).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The project aims at designing the first cognitive radio-based standard operating in the VHF-low UHF spectrum (TV spectrum).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In multi-carrier code-division multiple access (MC-CDMA), also known as OFDM-CDMA, OFDM is combined with CDMA spread spectrum communication for coding separation of the users.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Co-channel interference can be mitigated, meaning that manual fixed channel allocation (FCA) frequency planning is simplified, or complex dynamic channel allocation (DCA) schemes are avoided.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This is very beneficial in many countries, as it permits the operation of national single-frequency networks (SFN), where many transmitters send the same signal simultaneously over the same channel frequency.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] SFNs use the available spectrum more effectively than conventional multi-frequency broadcast networks (MFN), where program content is replicated on different carrier frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] SFNs also result in a diversity gain in receivers situated midway between the transmitters.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The coverage area is increased and the outage probability decreased in comparison to an MFN, due to increased received signal strength averaged over all subcarriers.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A rule of thumb for the maximum distance between transmitters in an SFN is equal to the distance a signal travels during the guard interval — for instance, a guard interval of 200 microseconds would allow transmitters to be spaced 60 km apart.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] A *single frequency network* is a form of transmitter macrodiversity.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The concept can be further used in *dynamic single-frequency networks* (DSFN), where the SFN grouping is changed from timeslot to timeslot.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM may be combined with other forms of space diversity, for example antenna arrays and MIMO channels.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This is done in the IEEE 802.11 Wireless LAN standards.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] An OFDM signal exhibits a high peak-to-average power ratio (PAPR) because the independent phases of the subcarriers mean that they will often combine constructively.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The linearity requirement is demanding, especially for transmitter RF output circuitry where amplifiers are often designed to be non-linear in order to minimise power consumption.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In practical OFDM systems a small amount of peak clipping is allowed to limit the PAPR in a judicious trade-off against the above consequences.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, the transmitter output filter which is required to reduce out-of-band spurs to legal levels has the effect of restoring peak levels that were clipped, so clipping is not an effective way to reduce PAPR.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Although the spectral efficiency of OFDM is attractive for both terrestrial and space communications, the high PAPR requirements have so far limited OFDM applications to terrestrial systems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] where CFc is the crest factor (in dB) for each subcarrier.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] (CFc is 3.01 dB for the sine waves used for BPSK and QPSK modulation).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] For example, the DVB-T signal in 2K mode is composed of 1705 subcarriers that are each QPSK-modulated, giving a crest factor of 35.32 dB.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Many PAPR (or crest factor) reduction techniques have been developed, for instance, based on iterative clipping.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Over the years, numerous model-driven approaches have been proposed to reduce the PAPR in communication systems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In recent years, there has been a growing interest in exploring data-driven models for PAPR reduction as part of ongoing research in end-to-end communication networks.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] These data-driven models offer innovative solutions and new avenues of exploration to address the challenges posed by high PAPR effectively.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] By leveraging data-driven techniques, researchers aim to enhance the performance and efficiency of communication networks by optimizing power utilization.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The dynamic range required for an FM receiver is 120 dB while DAB only require about 90 dB.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] As a comparison, each extra bit per sample increases the dynamic range by 6 dB.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The performance of any communication system can be measured in terms of its power efficiency and bandwidth efficiency.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The power efficiency describes the ability of communication system to preserve bit error rate (BER) of the transmitted signal at low power levels.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Bandwidth efficiency reflects how efficiently the allocated bandwidth is used and is defined as the throughput data rate per hertz in a given bandwidth.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] where $R_{s}$ is the symbol rate in giga-symbols per second (Gsps), $B_{\text{OFDM}}$ is the bandwidth of OFDM signal, and the factor of 2 is due to the two polarization states in the fiber.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] There is saving of bandwidth by using multicarrier modulation with orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] So the bandwidth for multicarrier system is less in comparison with single carrier system and hence bandwidth efficiency of multicarrier system is larger than single carrier system.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] There is only 1 dB increase in receiver power, but we get 76.7% improvement in bandwidth efficiency with using multicarrier transmission technique.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This section describes a simple idealized OFDM system model suitable for a time-invariant AWGN channel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] An OFDM carrier signal is the sum of a number of orthogonal subcarriers, with baseband data on each subcarrier being independently modulated commonly using some type of quadrature amplitude modulation (QAM) or phase-shift keying (PSK).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This composite baseband signal is typically used to modulate a main RF carrier.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] $s[n]$ is a serial stream of binary digits.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] By inverse multiplexing, these are first demultiplexed into N parallel streams, and each one mapped to a (possibly complex) symbol stream using some modulation constellation (QAM, PSK, etc.).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Note that the constellations may be different, so some streams may carry a higher bit-rate than others.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] An inverse FFT is computed on each set of symbols, giving a set of complex time-domain samples.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] These samples are then quadrature-mixed to passband in the standard way.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The real and imaginary components are first converted to the analogue domain using digital-to-analogue converters (DACs); the analogue signals are then used to modulate cosine and sine waves at the carrier frequency, $f_{\text{c}}$ , respectively.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] These signals are then summed to give the transmission signal, $s(t)$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The receiver picks up the signal $r(t)$ , which is then quadrature-mixed down to baseband using cosine and sine waves at the carrier frequency.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This also creates signals centered on $2f_{\text{c}}$ , so low-pass filters are used to reject these.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The baseband signals are then sampled and digitised using analog-to-digital converters (ADCs), and a forward FFT is used to convert back to the frequency domain.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This returns N parallel streams, each of which is converted to a binary stream using an appropriate symbol detector.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] These streams are then re-combined into a serial stream, ${\hat {s}}[n]$ , which is an estimate of the original binary stream at the transmitter.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If N subcarriers are used, and each subcarrier is modulated using M alternative symbols, the OFDM symbol alphabet consists of $M^{N}$ combined symbols.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] where $\{X_{k}\}$ are the data symbols, N is the number of subcarriers, and T is the OFDM symbol time.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] where $(\cdot )^{*}$ denotes the complex conjugate operator and $\delta \,$ is the Kronecker delta.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] To avoid intersymbol interference in multipath fading channels, a guard interval of length $T_{\text{g}}$ is inserted prior to the OFDM block.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] During this interval, a *cyclic prefix* is transmitted such that the signal in the interval $-T_{\text{g}}\leq t<0$ equals the signal in the interval $(T-T_{\text{g}})\leq t<T$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The low-pass signal filter above can be either real or complex-valued.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Real-valued low-pass equivalent signals are typically transmitted at baseband—wireline applications such as DSL use this approach.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] For wireless applications, the low-pass signal is typically complex-valued; in which case, the transmitted signal is up-converted to a carrier frequency $f_{\text{c}}$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Key features of some common OFDM-based systems are presented in the following table.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is used in ADSL connections that follow the ANSI T1.413 and G.dmt (ITU G.992.1) standards, where it is called *discrete multitone modulation* (DMT).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] DSL achieves high-speed data connections on existing copper wires.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is also used in the successor standards ADSL2, ADSL2+, VDSL, VDSL2, and G.fast.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] ADSL2 uses variable subcarrier modulation, ranging from BPSK to 32768QAM (in ADSL terminology this is referred to as bit-loading, or bit per tone, 1 to 15 bits per subcarrier).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Long copper wires suffer from attenuation at high frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The fact that OFDM can cope with this frequency selective attenuation and with narrow-band interference are the main reasons it is frequently used in applications such as ADSL modems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is used by many powerline devices to extend digital connections through power wiring.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Adaptive modulation is particularly important with such a noisy channel as electrical wiring.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Some medium speed smart metering modems, "Prime" and "G3" use OFDM at modest frequencies (30–100 kHz) with modest numbers of channels (several hundred) in order to overcome the intersymbol interference in the power line environment.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The IEEE 1901 standards include two incompatible physical layers that both use OFDM.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The ITU-T G.hn standard, which provides high-speed local area networking over existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables) is based on a PHY layer that specifies OFDM with adaptive modulation and a Low-Density Parity-Check (LDPC) FEC code.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is extensively used in wireless LAN and MAN applications, including IEEE 802.11a/g/n and WiMAX.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] IEEE 802.11a/g/n, operating in the 2.4 and 5 GHz bands, specifies per-stream airside data rates ranging from 6 to 54 Mbit/s.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] If both devices can use "HT mode" (added with 802.11n), the top 20 MHz per-stream rate is increased to 72.2 Mbit/s, with the option of data rates between 13.5 and 150 Mbit/s using a 40 MHz channel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Four different modulation schemes are used: BPSK, QPSK, 16-QAM, and 64-QAM, along with a set of error correcting rates (1/2–5/6).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The multitude of choices allows the system to adapt the optimum data rate for the current signal conditions.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] OFDM is also now being used in the WiMedia/Ecma-368 standard for high-speed wireless personal area networks in the 3.1–10.6 GHz ultrawideband spectrum (see MultiBand-OFDM).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Much of Europe and Asia has adopted OFDM for terrestrial broadcasting of digital television (DVB-T, DVB-H and T-DMB) and radio (EUREKA 147 DAB, Digital Radio Mondiale, HD Radio and T-DMB).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Customarily referred to as DVB-T, the standard calls for the exclusive use of COFDM for modulation.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] DVB-T is now widely used in Europe and elsewhere for terrestrial digital TV.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The ground segments of the Digital Audio Radio Service (SDARS) systems used by XM Satellite Radio and Sirius Satellite Radio are transmitted using Coded OFDM (COFDM).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The word "coded" comes from the use of forward error correction (FEC).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The question of the relative technical merits of COFDM versus 8VSB for terrestrial digital television has been a subject of some controversy, especially between European and North American technologists and regulators.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The United States has rejected several proposals to adopt the COFDM-based DVB-T system for its digital television services, and for many years has opted to use 8VSB (vestigial sideband modulation) exclusively for terrestrial digital television.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, in November 2017, the FCC approved a voluntary transition to ATSC 3.0, a new broadcast standard which is based on COFDM.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Unlike the first digital television transition in America, TV stations will not be assigned separate frequencies to transmit ATSC 3.0 and are not required to switch to ATSC 3.0 by any deadline.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Televisions sold in the U.S. are also not required to include ATSC 3.0 tuning capabilities.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Full-powered television stations are permitted to make the switch to ATSC 3.0, as long as they continue to make their main channel available through a simulcast agreement with another in-market station (with a similar coverage area) through at least November 2022.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] One of the major benefits provided by COFDM is in rendering radio broadcasts relatively immune to multipath distortion and signal fading due to atmospheric conditions or passing aircraft.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Proponents of COFDM argue it resists multipath far better than 8VSB.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Early 8VSB DTV (digital television) receivers often had difficulty receiving a signal.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Also, COFDM allows single-frequency networks, which is not possible with 8VSB.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, newer 8VSB receivers are far better at dealing with multipath, hence the difference in performance may diminish with advances in equalizer design.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The United States again uses an alternate standard, a proprietary system developed by iBiquity dubbed *HD Radio*.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] However, it uses COFDM as the underlying broadcast technology to add digital audio to AM (medium wave) and FM broadcasts.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Both Digital Radio Mondiale and HD Radio are classified as in-band on-channel systems, unlike Eureka 147 (DAB: Digital Audio Broadcasting) which uses separate VHF or UHF frequency bands instead.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Some forms of COFDM already offer this kind of hierarchical modulation, though BST-OFDM is intended to make it more flexible.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The 6 MHz television channel may therefore be "segmented", with different segments being modulated differently and used for different services.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] It is possible, for example, to send an audio service on a segment that includes a segment composed of a number of carriers, a data service on another segment and a television service on yet another segment—all within the same 6 MHz television channel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Furthermore, these may be modulated with different parameters so that, for example, the audio and data services could be optimized for mobile reception, while the television service is optimized for stationary reception in a high-multipath environment.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Ultra-wideband (UWB) wireless personal area network technology may also use OFDM, such as in Multiband OFDM (MB-OFDM).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] This UWB specification is advocated by the WiMedia Alliance (formerly by both the Multiband OFDM Alliance [MBOA] and the WiMedia Alliance, but the two have now merged), and is one of the competing UWB radio interfaces.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In Finland, the license holder Digita began deployment of a nationwide "@450" wireless network in parts of the country since April 2007.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] In February 2012 Datame announced they would upgrade the 450 MHz network to competing CDMA2000 technology.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Slovak Telekom in Slovakia offers Flash-OFDM connections with a maximum downstream speed of 5.3 Mbit/s, and a maximum upstream speed of 1.8 Mbit/s, with a coverage of over 70 percent of Slovak population.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The Flash-OFDM network was switched off in the majority of Slovakia on 30 September 2015.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] T-Mobile Germany used Flash-OFDM to backhaul Wi-Fi HotSpots on the Deutsche Bahn's ICE high speed trains between 2005 and 2015, until switching over to UMTS and LTE.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] American wireless carrier Nextel Communications field tested wireless broadband network technologies including Flash-OFDM in 2005.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Sprint purchased the carrier in 2006 and decided to deploy the mobile version of WiMAX, which is based on Scalable Orthogonal Frequency-Division Multiple Access (SOFDMA) technology.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] Citizens Telephone Cooperative launched a mobile broadband service based on Flash-OFDM technology to subscribers in parts of Virginia in March 2006.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The maximum speed available was 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p01] The service was discontinued on April 30, 2009.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] VOFDM was proposed by Xiang-Gen Xia in 2000 (*Proceedings of ICC 2000*, New Orleans, and *IEEE Trans. on Communications*, Aug.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] 2001) for single transmit antenna systems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] VOFDM replaces each scalar value in the conventional OFDM by a vector value and is a bridge between OFDM and the single carrier frequency domain equalizer (SC-FDE).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] When the vector size is 1 , it is OFDM and when the vector size is at least the channel length and the FFT size is 1 , it is SC-FDE.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] In VOFDM, assume M is the vector size, and each scalar-valued signal $X_{n}$ in OFDM is replaced by a vector-valued signal ${\bf {X}}_{n}$ of vector size M , $0\leq n\leq N-1$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] One takes the N -point IFFT of ${\bf {X}}_{n},0\leq n\leq N-1$ , component-wisely and gets another vector sequence of the same vector size M , ${\bf {x}}_{k},0\leq k\leq N-1$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] This vector sequence is converted to a scalar sequence by sequentializing all the vectors of size M , which is transmitted at a transmit antenna sequentially.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] At the receiver, the received scalar sequence is first converted to the vector sequence of vector size M .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] where ${\textstyle H_{m}(z)=\sum _{l}h_{Ml+m}z^{-l}}$ is the m th polyphase component of the channel $H(z),0\leq m\leq M-1$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] From (1), one can see that the original ISI channel is converted to N many vector subchannels of vector size M .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] There is no ISI across these vector subchannels but there is ISI inside each vector subchannel.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] In each vector subchannel, at most M many symbols are interfered each other.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Clearly, when the vector size $M=1$ , the above VOFDM returns to OFDM and when $M>L$ and $N=1$ , it becomes the SC-FDE.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] The vector size M is a parameter that one can choose freely and properly in practice and controls the ISI level.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] There may be a trade-off between vector size M , demodulation complexity at the receiver, and FFT size, for a given channel bandwidth.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Equation (1) is mathematically new for an ISI channel, when the vector size $M>1$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Note that the length of the CP part in the sequential form does not have to be an integer multiple of the vector size, $\Gamma M$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] One can truncate the above vectorized CP to a sequential CP of length not less than the ISI channel length, which will not affect the above demodulation.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Also note that there exist many other different generalizations/forms of OFDM, to see their essential differences, it is critical to see their corresponding received signal equations to demodulate.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] The above VOFDM is the earliest and the only one that achieves the received signal equation (1) and/or its equivalent form, although it may have different implementations at transmitter vs. different IFFT algorithms.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] It has been shown (Yabo Li et al., *IEEE Trans. on Signal Processing*, Oct.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] 2012) that applying the MMSE linear receiver to each vector subchannel (1), it achieves multipath diversity and/or signal space diversity.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] This is because the vectorized channel matrices in (1) are pseudo-circulant and can be diagonalized by the M -point DFT/IDFT matrix with some diagonal phase shift matrices.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] It may collect the multipath diversity and/or signal space diversity similar to the precoding to collect the signal space diversity for single antenna systems to combat wireless fading or the diagonal space-time block coding to collect the spatial diversity for multiple antenna systems.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] The details are referred to the IEEE TCOM and IEEE TSP papers mentioned above.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] OFDM has become an interesting technique for power line communications (PLC).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] In this area of research, a wavelet transform is introduced to replace the DFT as the method of creating orthogonal frequencies.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] This is due to the advantages wavelets offer, which are particularly useful on noisy power lines.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] On the receiver side, an analysis bank is used to demodulate the signal again.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] followed by another N -band transmultiplexer.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] An example of W-OFDM uses the Perfect Reconstruction Cosine Modulated Filter Bank (PR-CMFB) and Extended Lapped Transform (ELT) is used for the wavelet TF.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] These two functions are their respective inverses, and can be used to modulate and demodulate a given input sequence.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Just as in the case of DFT, the wavelet transform creates orthogonal waves with $\textstyle f_{0}$ , $\textstyle f_{1}$ , ..., $\textstyle f_{N-1}$ .
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] The orthogonality ensures that they do not interfere with each other and can be sent simultaneously.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] At the receiver, $\textstyle g_{0}$ , $\textstyle g_{1}$ , ..., $\textstyle g_{N-1}$ are used to reconstruct the data sequence once more.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] W-OFDM is an evolution of the standard OFDM, with certain advantages.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] Mainly, the sidelobe levels of W-OFDM are lower.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] This results in less ICI, as well as greater robustness to narrowband interference.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] These two properties are especially useful in PLC, where most of the lines aren't shielded against EM-noise, which creates noisy channels and noise spikes.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] A comparison between the two modulation techniques also reveals that the complexity of both algorithms remains approximately the same.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] The vast majority of implementations of OFDM use the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] However, there exist other orthogonal transforms that can be used.
[src:lte-networks/orthogonal-frequency-division-multiplexing-p02] For example, OFDM systems based on the discrete Hartley transform (DHT) and the wavelet transform have been investigated.
